          <figcaption class="in-figcap">FIG&nbsp;4 — what looks like three hook systems is one unified <code>PluginManager._hooks</code> dict plus the gateway's separate <code>HookRegistry</code>.</figcaption>
        </figure>

        <h3 class="in-h3">Shell hook wire protocol</h3>
        <p>Hermes writes JSON to <code>stdin</code> of the hook command and parses JSON from <code>stdout</code>. The parser accepts both Hermes-native (<code>action</code>) and Claude Code-shaped (<code>decision</code>) block keys — explicit compatibility move. Default timeout 60s, max 300s, configurable per spec.</p>

        <pre class="in-code"><code>{`# stdin Hermes writes:
{
  "hook_event_name": "pre_tool_call",
  "tool_name": "terminal",
  "tool_input": { "command": "echo hello" },
  "session_id": "sess_abc123",
  "cwd": "/home/user/project",
  "extra": {}
}

# stdout Hermes accepts (either form):
{ "decision": "block", "reason": "Forbidden command" }
{ "action":   "block", "message": "Forbidden command" }

# pre_llm_call context injection:
{ "context": "Today is Friday" }`}</code></pre>

        <h3 class="in-h3">Allowlist machinery</h3>
        <p><code>~/.hermes/shell-hooks-allowlist.json</code> stores <code>(event, command)</code> approval pairs. Lookup is pure key-equality: <code>script_mtime_at_approval</code> is recorded but not checked. A modified hook script with a stale allowlist entry is silently accepted. Bypass via <code>--accept-hooks</code> CLI flag, <code>HERMES_ACCEPT_HOOKS=1</code> env, or <code>hooks_auto_accept: true</code> in config.</p>
      </section>

      <!-- ===== §5 PERSISTENCE ===== -->
      <section id="s5" class="in-mod">
        <header class="in-mod-h">
          <span class="in-mod-n">05</span>
          <h2>Persistence — SQLite v11</h2>
          <span class="in-mod-tag">storage</span>
        </header>

        <p class="in-tldr"><b>TL;DR.</b> <code>~/.hermes/state.db</code> is at schema version 11. Two main tables (<code>sessions</code> 29 columns, <code>messages</code> 15 columns), a key-value <code>state_meta</code>, a <code>schema_version</code> tracker, plus two FTS5 virtual tables for unicode and CJK substring search. All writes use <code>BEGIN IMMEDIATE</code> with random 20–150ms jitter to avoid SQLite WAL convoy.</p>

        <p>The <code>sessions</code> table is unusually rich for an "open source agent" tool. It tracks per-session cost (estimated AND actual), token breakdown across input / output / cache-read / cache-write / reasoning, billing provider, billing mode, pricing version, handoff state. This is production-grade billing telemetry baked into the open-source schema.</p>

