          <figcaption class="in-figcap">FIG&nbsp;6 — gateway pipeline. AIAgent is LRU-cached per session key; one Hermes process handles many concurrent conversations.</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <!-- WRAP -->
      <section class="in-wrap">
        <h2 class="in-h">▸ TAKE-AWAYS</h2>
        <ul class="in-wrap-list">
          <li><b>The architecture is more pragmatic than principled.</b> Two parallel CLI codebases, flat-root Python files, an embedded Kanban board — what shipped early stayed, and accretion is the unifying force.</li>
          <li><b>The hook surface is simpler than it looks.</b> One dispatcher (<code>PluginManager._hooks</code>) does most of the work; the "3 systems" framing exists because the registration <i>paths</i> are different even though the runtime is unified.</li>
          <li><b>The session is the unit of accounting, not the conversation.</b> Cost, tokens, billing mode are session-level. Compression spawns new sessions linked by <code>parent_session_id</code> — the chain is the conversation.</li>
          <li><b>The CJK trigram index is the leak.</b> Hermes's open-source codebase quietly exposes the size of its WeChat / Feishu / DingTalk user base — multilingual substring search is not an idle decision.</li>
          <li><b>The docs lag the code.</b> <code>pre_gateway_dispatch</code>, "6 categories", and "3 concurrent subagents" are wrong or unconfirmable. Read source for anything load-bearing.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="in-wrap-foot">
          Source-grounded against <a href="https://github.com/NousResearch/hermes-agent/releases/tag/v2026.5.16" rel="noopener">NousResearch/hermes-agent@v2026.5.16</a>. Methodology: three parallel reverse-engineering passes via raw GitHub file fetches; every claim cites a file path. Cycle this page against a newer tag when v0.15 lands.
        </p>
      </section>

